
# Blue-Carbon TTF (Manglar Tumbes) — 10-Slide Executive Pitch Deck Outline

---

## Slide 1 — Title & Hook

**Slide Title:** *Blue-Carbon TTF: Tokenizing the Mangroves of Tumbes*

**Core Objective:** Establish identity and stakes in five seconds — this is a real, deployed protocol protecting a specific, named ecosystem, not a generic concept.

**Visual Layout & Graphics Suggestion:** Full-bleed background photo of the Tumbes mangrove canopy at water level; project name and tagline centered; small LACNet + hackathon logos bottom corner.

**Talking Points:**
- "Blue-Carbon TTF is a multijurisdictional Web3 protocol that turns verified mangrove restoration into tradeable climate assets."
- "Built on LACNet, piloted in the Santuario Nacional Los Manglares de Tumbes — Peru's largest mangrove sanctuary."
- "Today we'll show you a functional testnet, live dashboard, and 3-year growth plan."

---

## Slide 2 — The Blue Carbon Opportunity

**Slide Title:** *Blue Carbon: The Ocean's Climate Advantage*

**Core Objective:** Educate non-technical judges on why mangroves matter more, per hectare, than most terrestrial forests — before pitching the tech.

**Visual Layout & Graphics Suggestion:** Side-by-side comparison graphic: "Terrestrial Forest" vs. "Mangrove / Blue Carbon Ecosystem" carbon sequestration rate icons; below it, a callout stat box for the Tumbes Sanctuary.

**Talking Points:**
- "Coastal blue carbon ecosystems — mangroves, marshes, seagrass — cover roughly 50 million hectares worldwide."
- "Mangroves sequester carbon at rates far exceeding most terrestrial forests, while also buffering coastlines from storms."
- "The Santuario Nacional Los Manglares de Tumbes alone stores an estimated 1.78 million megagrams of carbon — about 6.55 million tonnes of CO2."

---

## Slide 3 — The Core Problem

**Slide Title:** *Protected on Paper, Threatened in Practice*

**Core Objective:** Show the judges a concrete, local threat (not an abstract global one) and name who is being left out economically.

**Visual Layout & Graphics Suggestion:** Photo or icon of shrimp-farming ponds (*langostineras*) encroaching on mangrove; simple flow diagram showing "Carbon Credit Revenue" bypassing a small icon labeled "Coastal Cooperatives."

**Talking Points:**
- "Despite protected status, the sanctuary is degraded by illegal deforestation for shrimp-farming ponds, releasing sequestered carbon back into the atmosphere."
- "The deeper issue is economic: coastal cooperatives who depend on crab, shrimp, and *concha negra* harvesting are structurally excluded from the carbon-credit value chain their own conservation work enables."
- "Traditional carbon registries offer these communities no direct, transparent share of the revenue their ecosystem generates."

---

## Slide 4 — Traditional Registries vs. Web3 (The Gap)

**Slide Title:** *Why Centralized Carbon Registries Fail*

**Core Objective:** Build the case for blockchain specifically — not as a buzzword, but as a fix for named, verifiable failures.

**Visual Layout & Graphics Suggestion:** Two-column comparison table/graphic: "Traditional Centralized Registries" (red icons: opacity, greenwashing risk, high fees) vs. "Blue-Carbon TTF on LACNet" (green icons: on-chain transparency, zero gas fees, multijurisdictional).

**Talking Points:**
- "Centralized registries are vulnerable to greenwashing and double-counting because issuance logic isn't independently verifiable."
- "They're also siloed — a credit issued in one country's registry has no portability to another."
- "LACNet's zero-GAS-fee testnet removes the cost barrier that would otherwise exclude smaller cooperatives from participating."

---

## Slide 5 — The Solution (Blue-Carbon TTF)

**Slide Title:** *From Verified Hectare to On-Chain Credit*

**Core Objective:** Explain, in one clean flow, exactly what the protocol does end-to-end.

**Visual Layout & Graphics Suggestion:** Horizontal flowchart: "Drone/Satellite MRV Data" → "MRV Oracle Verification" → "Smart Contract Minting" → "TTF Credit (tCO2eq) in Wallet."

**Talking Points:**
- "Blue-Carbon TTF converts drone- and satellite-verified restoration data into Transferable Tokenized Framework credits, denominated in tCO2eq."
- "Each credit is minted directly on-chain — auditable in real time by anyone, not just the issuing authority."
- "This replaces a trust-based, opaque process with a verify-then-mint pipeline."

---

## Slide 6 — Technical Architecture & Zero-Gas Model

**Slide Title:** *Built for Zero-Cost, Multijurisdictional Scale*

**Core Objective:** Give technical judges enough substance to trust the engineering, without losing non-technical judges.

**Visual Layout & Graphics Suggestion:** Simple architecture diagram: Remix IDE → Solidity Contract → LACNet Open Pro-Testnet (EVM) → BaseRelayRecipient (gasless layer) → IPFS (data pinning); use the same visual language as the live dashboard's terminal log.

**Talking Points:**
- "Contracts are written and deployed via Remix IDE onto the LACNet Open Pro-Testnet — an EVM-compatible chain with zero gas fees."
- "The BaseRelayRecipient layer enables gasless meta-transactions, so coastal cooperatives never need to hold native gas tokens to participate."
- "Verification imagery and MRV data are pinned to IPFS, creating a tamper-evident, decentralized audit trail."

---

## Slide 7 — Tokenomics & Community-Centered Distribution

**Slide Title:** *55% Goes Directly to the Coast*

**Core Objective:** Prove the "community-first" claim with a hard number, not just a mission statement.

**Visual Layout & Graphics Suggestion:** The donut/pie chart already built for the project: Coastal Communities 55%, Technology/Platform 20%, MRV Verification 15%, Nursery Reinvestment 10%.

**Talking Points:**
- "Every single TTF minting event is split automatically by smart contract — no manual disbursement, no discretion."
- "55% goes directly to the coastal cooperatives who steward the restored hectares."
- "The remaining 45% is fully accounted for: platform upkeep, independent MRV verification, and reinvestment into mangrove nurseries."

---

## Slide 8 — The 3R Circular Economy Framework

**Slide Title:** *Reduce, Reuse, Recycle — On-Chain*

**Core Objective:** Show judges that the token has real utility beyond speculation — it closes a loop.

**Visual Layout & Graphics Suggestion:** Three-icon row: ♻️ Reduce (corporate offset/burn), 🌱 Reuse (nursery reinvestment from pruning waste), 🎣 Recycle (ecotourism & fishing-quota access) — matching the dashboard's action panel.

**Talking Points:**
- "Reduce: corporations and individuals can burn TTF credits to offset their own verified emissions."
- "Reuse: a share of every transaction reinvests directly into mangrove nurseries, funding the next restoration cycle."
- "Recycle: cooperatives can redeem accumulated TTF for ecotourism access or fishing-quota privileges — creating tangible, local utility."

---

## Slide 9 — Pilot Traction & Projected KPIs

**Slide Title:** *Proof of Concept, Proof of Scale*

**Core Objective:** Convert the audience from "interesting idea" to "already working, and here's the growth math."

**Visual Layout & Graphics Suggestion:** The KPI growth bar/line chart already built (Hectares, Cooperatives, TTF minted across Year 1–3), plus a small callout box for the four pilot stats.

**Talking Points:**
- "In the pilot phase alone: 40 hectares verified, 860 TTF credits minted, 9 active coastal cooperatives, and a 22% increase in *concha negra* capture in restored zones."
- "Our 3-year projection scales to 800 hectares and 17,200 TTF credits minted, expanding from Peru into Ecuador and Colombia."
- "The architecture was multijurisdictional from day one — this isn't a future rebuild, it's already parameterized."

